node.text: I feel blessed each and every day, the opportunity to photograph and capture video in this city is enchanting. From sun up to sun down, through every season. This city thrives. It is loud, unapologetic and unique. There’s a constant energy that runs through the streets, a power that exists around each corner. This is home and I wanted to share a bit of it with you.

node.text:
I think many of you reading this have had some sort of experience with loving the wrong person, and many of you have discovered that this person is also a narcissist. 

Getting over and putting distance between yourself and a narcissist can be a really difficult thing to do. For one, being with the wrong person and trying to maintain a relationship with someone who intends to hurt you can be mentally and emotionally exhausting. So, when the time comes to walk away, you find out that you may not have the strength to do so as you've used up so much energy to try and remain strong despite the pain they've caused.

I want to speak directly to the person who is currently struggling with the heartache of caring for the wrong person, and I'm writing this to the person who might have difficulty keeping a narcissist out of their life and or heart.

You are meant for so much more despite all that you've faced, and you have to stop blaming yourself and maybe give yourself a bit more credit. You can always help who you love, and just because you love a person doesn't mean they'll help you toward your journey for peace of mind and happiness. You fell for this person because they were good at pretending to be the type of person you could fall for, and you struggle to leave at times because what you feel for them is genuine despite the hurt they've caused you.

If you are strong enough to love, you are also strong enough to let go if what you love is hurting you. It takes time, be patient with yourself. 

What are your experiences with a #narcissist, and for those of you who have made it out, what is your advice to someone struggling to move on?

node.text:
It's wild how some of you have been lied to for so long that you believe that this man is on here liking multiple women's photos because he's bored? You're the same one surprised when you figure out that he's cheating on you or entertaining someone that isn't you when the truth has been in front of you this entire time. They attempt to manipulate you by labeling you insecure; they silence you by making you feel like you're overreacting to their attempts to fool you into believing that what they do is okay. ⁠
⁠
Maybe I'm saying this for the simple fact that I don't have any use for social media outside of using it as a tool to reach you with these words to help. I have real hobbies, solid interests, respect for my partner, and a whole life away from this thing that is often used to make you feel less than or neglected, but I don't think you should ever have to force yourself to be okay with actions that make you feel bad or upset your emotionally. Confidence has nothing to do with allowing a man the opportunity to make you look like a fool and pay no mind to anyone who has built their self-worth, confidence, or security on being blind to the fucked up things that men do.⁠
⁠
The same ones who are proud of themselves for openly pretending that being secure means letting him get away with emotionally harmful and disrespectful shit are the same ones asking me how he could cheat on them.⁠
⁠
Ladies, it's okay to be bothered by what you're bothered by, and it's okay to leave a man who refuses to do better. It's okay to leave a man who demeans you and belittles your feelings. And it's okay to lose a friend who tells you otherwise.
